# 🔧 Auditor Dashboard RuntimeBinderException Fix - COMPLETE SOLUTION

## Problem
When accessing the Auditor Dashboard, users received an **Internal Server Error** with the following exception:

```
RuntimeBinderException: Cannot convert type 'System.Collections.Generic.List<<f_AnonymousType16<System.DateTime,string,string,string>> to 'System.Collections.Generic.List<object>'
```

This error occurred in `AuditorDashboard.cshtml` when trying to cast ViewBag data to dynamic lists.

## Root Cause Analysis
The issue had **TWO parts**:

### Part 1: Controller ViewBag Assignment (Already Fixed)
ViewBag collections were assigned without properly casting to dynamic types:
```csharp
// ❌ BEFORE
ViewBag.AuditLogs = logsDisplay;  // Anonymous type list
ViewBag.FinancialAuditData = financialAudit;  // Anonymous type list  
ViewBag.OperationalAuditData = operationalAudit;  // Entity list
```

### Part 2: View Runtime Casting (NEW FIX)
The view was attempting to cast ViewBag properties to `List<dynamic>` at runtime:
```razor
<!-- ❌ BEFORE - This caused the error -->
@if (ViewBag.AuditLogs != null && ((List<dynamic>)ViewBag.AuditLogs).Count > 0)
```

This explicit cast at runtime failed because:
- The anonymous type list couldn't be directly cast to `List<dynamic>`
- Runtime binder couldn't handle the type conversion
- The cast happened AFTER the controller assignment

## Solution Applied

### Part 1: Controller Fix
Added explicit `.Cast<dynamic>().ToList()` in `DashboardController.cs`:

```csharp
// ✅ AFTER
ViewBag.AuditLogs = logsDisplay.Cast<dynamic>().ToList();
ViewBag.FinancialAuditData = financialAudit.Cast<dynamic>().ToList();
ViewBag.OperationalAuditData = operationalAudit.Cast<dynamic>().ToList();
```

### Part 2: View Fix (NEW)
Removed explicit casting in `AuditorDashboard.cshtml`. Use ViewBag properties directly:

**Before (Failed)**:
```razor
@if (ViewBag.AuditLogs != null && ((List<dynamic>)ViewBag.AuditLogs).Count > 0)
```

**After (Works)**:
```razor
@if (ViewBag.AuditLogs != null && ViewBag.AuditLogs.Count > 0)
```

This works because:
- The controller already converted to `List<dynamic>`
- Razor can access dynamic properties without explicit casting
- The `.Count` property works on dynamic lists
- No runtime casting errors occur

### Changes Made

**File 1: Controllers/DashboardController.cs**
- Added `.Cast<dynamic>().ToList()` to all ViewBag collections in `LoadAuditorKPIDataAsync()`

**File 2: Views/Dashboard/AuditorDashboard.cshtml**
- Removed `((List<dynamic>)...)` casts from 3 table sections:
  1. Audit Logs table
  2. Financial Audit Summary table
  3. Operational Audit Summary table

## Technical Explanation

### Why the Original Approach Failed

```csharp
// This was the problem flow:
var logsDisplay = auditLogs.Select(a => new { ... }).ToList();  
// Type: List<AnonymousType>

ViewBag.AuditLogs = logsDisplay;  
// Type: dynamic (but internally List<AnonymousType>)

// Later in Razor view:
((List<dynamic>)ViewBag.AuditLogs)  
// ❌ Runtime tries to cast List<AnonymousType> to List<dynamic>
// ❌ This fails because they're not compatible types
```

### Why the Fix Works

```csharp
// New approach:
var logsDisplay = auditLogs.Select(a => new { ... }).ToList();
// Type: List<AnonymousType>

logsDisplay.Cast<dynamic>().ToList();
// ✅ Explicitly converts each item to dynamic
// ✅ Returns: List<dynamic>

ViewBag.AuditLogs = ...Cast<dynamic>().ToList();
// Type: dynamic (but internally List<dynamic>)

// Later in Razor view:
ViewBag.AuditLogs.Count > 0
// ✅ Works! Already a List<dynamic>, no casting needed
```

